s are pigment stones","Most gallstones are pure cholesterol","Most gallstones are calcium carbonate","Most gallstones are mixed cholesterol stones"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn Western populations, approximately 80% of gallstones are cholesterol-based. \u003Cstrong\u003EMost gallstones are mixed cholesterol stones\u003C/strong\u003E containing both cholesterol and calcium salts. Due to their cholesterol content, these stones are typically radiolucent, making \u003Cstrong\u003Eradiopaque\u003C/strong\u003E stones less common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPigment stones\u003C/strong\u003E comprise only about 20% of gallstones in Western populations and are more common in Asian populations. They contain calcium bilirubinate and are often associated with haemolytic conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003EPure cholesterol\u003C/strong\u003E stones are relatively uncommon, accounting for only about 10% of all cholesterol stones. \u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium carbonate\u003C/strong\u003E stones are rare.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholesterol stones account for 80% of gallstones in Western populations","Most gallstones are radiolucent due to their cholesterol content","Pigment stones contain calcium bilirubinate and are less common in Western populations"],"references":["Dave HD, Shumway KR, Al Obaidi NM. Physiology, Biliary. [Updated 2022 Dec 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537107/","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N